{"id": "f7erxq", "title": "Has anyone else here been keeping up with the $S (Sprint) Stock and $TMUS (T-Mobile Us Inc) Merge News?", "selftext": "Just curious if anyone else here has been watching the news and updates for the pending Merger between Sprint &amp; T-Mobile, and if so , what you feel this brings for the future of the combined company &amp; share holders?   \n\n\nYesterday T-Mobile posted a Headline on their news site:  \n\"Companies drive forward toward closing the merger to become the New T-Mobile as early as April 1, 2020\"  \n\n\nTo Further Quote:  \n\u201cWith today\u2019s agreement in place, we are now turning our attention toward our goal of closing this transaction and creating the New T-Mobile as early as April 1, 2020,\u201d said Mike Sievert, COO and President of T-Mobile, and appointed CEO of the company starting on May 1, 2020. \u201cWe are on the verge of being able to do what we\u2019ve set out to do from day one -- reshape a broken wireless industry and create the new standard for consumers when it comes to value, speed, quality and service. The New T-Mobile is literally going to change wireless for good and now we\u2019re almost ready to get to the fun part: bringing our teams together, building this supercharged Un-carrier and becoming the envy of the wireless industry and beyond!\u201d  \nLink: [https://www.t-mobile.com/news/t-mobile-sprint-business-combination-agreement](https://www.t-mobile.com/news/t-mobile-sprint-business-combination-agreement)  \n\n\nForbes also broke down some of the key points of the recent revision to the agreement: \n\n* Deutsche Telekom is now set to own 43% of the combined company (up from below 42% when the deal was first announced almost two years ago), while SoftBank\u2019s ownership stake will drop to around 24% from 27%, according to the announcement.\n* Common shareholders of Sprint won\u2019t see a change in the exchange ratio, which was originally set at 9.75 Sprint shares for each T-Mobile share.\n* But under the revised merger agreement, SoftBank, which owns nearly 85% of Sprint common stock, will exchange 11 shares for each T-Mobile share, giving Deutsche Telekom a slightly larger stake in the new company.\n* The German telecoms company, which owns more than 60% of T-Mobile U.S., was [expected to seek](https://www.forbes.com/sites/sergeiklebnikov/2020/02/13/t-mobile-parent-deutsche-telekom-seeking-to-renegotiate-price-of-sprint-merger-report/#48199316471d) a reduced purchase price for Sprint because its share price and performance have deteriorated since the agreed upon merger price two years ago.\n* SoftBank agreed to give up [48.8 million](https://www.wsj.com/articles/sprint-t-mobile-near-agreement-on-new-merger-terms-11582230987?mod=hp_lead_pos2) T-Mobile shares to the combined company, which will operate under the T-Mobile name, but if the merged company\u2019s stock price [reaches $150](https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/20/sprint-t-mobile-to-give-deutsche-telekom-slightly-higher-stake-after-merger.html) between 2022 and 2025, those shares could be reissued to SoftBank.\n* Both companies said on Thursday that they plan to finalize the merger as soon as April 1, which sent Sprint shares up more than 4% after the announcement while T-Mobile shares fell 1.5%.\n\nLink: [https://www.forbes.com/sites/sergeiklebnikov/2020/02/21/sprint-and-t-mobile-renegotiate-merger-agreement-giving-deutsche-telekom-a-bigger-ownership-stake/#1c9111df49e4](https://www.forbes.com/sites/sergeiklebnikov/2020/02/21/sprint-and-t-mobile-renegotiate-merger-agreement-giving-deutsche-telekom-a-bigger-ownership-stake/#1c9111df49e4)", "created_utc": 1582307457, "permalink": "/r/wallstreetbets/comments/f7erxq/has_anyone_else_here_been_keeping_up_with_the_s/", "is_self": true}